{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ab85821d-ad93-4b75-876a-6fdca5020c4f","content":"A **NullReferenceException** is an application-level bug, not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs only cover how `mscoree.dll` selects and loads the .NET runtime — they won't contain information about your exception.\n\n**To diagnose a NullReferenceException, try these instead:**\n\n1. **Read the stack trace** — it tells you exactly which line has the null reference.\n2. **Enable first-chance exception logging** — run with a debugger attached or use `dotnet-dump` / `dotnet-trace`.\n3. **Check Event Viewer** (Windows) — look under Application logs for the crash details.\n\nIf you share the **exception stack trace** or a **crash dump**, I can help pinpoint the bug. Would you like help with any of those approaches?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"83826ea2-c395-480b-a3b7-28643c4caabc","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking me to analyze CLR activation logs to diagnose a NullReferenceException in their .NET app. Let me check if there's a relevant skill for this.\n\nLooking at the available skills, I see \"clr-activation-debugging\" which \"Diagnoses .NET Framework CLR activation issues using CLR activation logs (CLRLoad logs) produced by mscoree.dll.\"\n\nHowever, a NullReferenceException after startup is not a CLR activation issue. CLR activation logs deal with runtime selection/loading by the shim (mscoree.dll) — things like picking the wrong runtime version, failing to load a runtime, or unexpected Feature-on-Demand dialogs. A NullReferenceException is an application-level bug, not a CLR activation problem.\n\n\nI need to clarify this distinction with the user and point them toward more suitable debugging approaches like examining stack traces, using a debugger, or analyzing application logs instead.","outputTokens":391,"requestId":"204D:39211A:62AD81:7323C9:69F00DD0"},"id":"d01dd030-3417-478e-b5c9-f8029b48556b","timestamp":"2026-04-28T01:31: